{"kind":"textbox","id":"sh/bqt0ryt8","slide":2,"name":"text","text":"New number. New account. Same campaign.","textPreview":"New number. New account. Same campaign.","textChars":39,"textLines":1,"bbox":[62,572,420,32]}
{"kind":"textbox","id":"sh/apkjytsn","slide":2,"name":"text","text":"Sources: Vietnam MIC / Information Security Authority","textPreview":"Sources: Vietnam MIC / Information Security Authority","textChars":53,"textLines":1,"bbox":[62,656,410,18]}
{"kind":"image","id":"im/2x0j61k7","slide":2,"name":"","alt":"Vietnam illuminated by connected scam signals and campaign clusters","bbox":[0,0,1280,720]}
{"kind":"notes","id":"nt/pajsl9","slide":2,"text":"This is already happening at scale in Vietnam. In the first ten months of 2024, authorities received more than 220,000 online-fraud reports—most connected to financial and banking scams. In the first week of 2025 alone, another 6,685 reports were submitted.\nThe difficult part is that scammers constantly change phone numbers, accounts, domains and QR codes. Each report looks different, but the campaign behind it is often the same."}
